<TEXT>
ronald reagan and mikhail s gorbachev who 
have made arms control history together are bound to revisit their 
idea of a dramatic reduction in strategic weapons when they meet 
over lunch this week but a nudge forward rather than a 
breakthrough is the most thats likely to result 
the strategic arms reduction treaty that they have been talking 
about the hopedfor centerpiece in reagans arms control program 
has too many holes in it for gorbachev and reagan to reach command 
decisions during their threehour luncheon wednesday on governors 
island in new york harbor 
moreover gorbachev is well aware that he is dealing with a lame 
duck president who will have six weeks left in office and will be in 
no position to commit his successor george bush to any course of 
action 
for all that max m kampelman the chief us arms control 
negotiator finds it difficult to believe arms will not be discussed 
during lunch 
i believe it will come up kampelman said in an interview 
last week but i dont believe it will come up in a negotiating 
context my own judgment is it will come up as a discussion and 
maybe a quick review of where things stand now 
kampelman added and i guess perhaps an expression on both 
sides they hope to finish the work i cannot myself envisage any 
detailed discussion of the arms negotiations taking place 
the unfinished strategic arms treaty will be turned over to 
presidentelect bushs administration with the us side hopes a 
renewed commitment from gorbachev to maintain its current high 
priority 
in a report to congress on friday reagan accused the soviet 
union of violating existing arms control agreements with the united 
states we cannot conclude new strategic arms control agreements 
while this violation remains uncorrected the report said 
the report cited krasnoyarsk a siberian radar installation that 
the administration contends violates the 1972 antiballistic missile 
treaty 
however reagan did not accuse the soviets of a material 
breach of the agreement which could have led to its unraveling 
and national security adviser colin d powell said reagan was not 
expected to make a major issue of the us allegations in the 
meeting with gorbachev 
reagan intends to raise arms control issues with the soviet 
leader just as he will bring up the suspended red army withdrawal 
from afghanistan and the human rights situation officials say 
but the vital ground work simply has not been undertaken this 
time for example secretary of state george p shultz did not have 
a planning session with foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze to 
set an agenda and to define the issues for their leaders 
arms negotiations were adjourned in geneva on nov 15 and the two 
sides have not met since 
they ended the 10th round of talks agreeing to an early 
resumption in 1989 the united states subsequently proposed feb 15 
the soviets did not respond 
reagan and bush probably will have shultz and a handful of other 
senior us officials at the luncheon table with them but the us 
and soviet arms control experts who normally labor over the details 
while the leaders hold their summits plan no such sessions 
shultz has predicted a substantive discussion another us 
official mindful of gorbachevs innovative style remarked you 
never can tell 
but the hard fact is that the treaty to reduce us and soviet 
armories of longrange bombers missiles and submarines by 30 to 50 
percent is still mired in disagreement on several key points 
the two sides have not decided for instance whether to include 
mobile missiles or sealaunched cruise missiles both are extremely 
hard to track that means cutbacks are hard to verify the room for 
cheating is uncomfortably wide 
the soviets meanwhile still would like to restrict reagans 
strategic defense initiative as part of a treaty deal the 4 
billionayear program is designed to stop ballistic missiles in 
space but critics here and in moscow say it could extend the arms 
race to a new and dangerous sphere 
then there is the fact a new us administration is coming 
aboard one that may not share the outgoing administrations views 
on reducing strategic weapons 
brent scowcroft designated by bush to be his national security 
adviser is worried that large cutbacks in us strategic weapons 
could make the warsaw pacts edge in conventional forces in europe 
more significant 
he also is concerned that reducing the us arsenal of landbased 
intercontinental ballistic missiles could expose those that remain 
to a higher risk of being destroyed in the event of a soviet attack 
bush will be at the table deferring to reagan it will be 
president reagans meeting he said 
and yet reagan will be aware that in a sense he will be 
speaking also for bush and should not commit his successor to 
positions he may not want to take after jan 20 
