the melding of communism and democracy under 
mikhail s gorbachev is long overdue americas top communist said 
on the eve of the soviet leaders visit 
for years ive been saying the socialist countries should move 
in a democratic direction said gus hall general secretary of the 
70yearold communist party usa theres no big threat they 
can afford it 
it is true of any society certain things get stuck and 
changes dont take place corresponding to the new conditions its 
necessary to shake up a society he said socialism had reached 
a level where some of the negatives had piled up somebody had to 
provide a lead moving them to a higher state 
glasnost and peace initiatives were among the topics on halls 
mind as he and other americans awaited gorbachevs visit to new york 
tuesday through thursday the soviet leader will address the united 
nations general assembly and meet with president reagan and 
presidentelect george bush 
ive met gorbachev before he became general secretary and then 
since said hall 78 who has been employed fulltime as general 
secretary of the american communist party since 1959 and has run for 
president four times since 1972 
hes of a different generation and therefore in many ways 
hes easier to deal with hes very friendly and outgoing and easy 
to talk to if you express differences it doesnt seem personal 
with him hall said of gorbachev hes not afraid to try 
glasnost calls for trial and error and he seems to be very bold 
in trying new ideas 
this is a historic moment in the socialist countries they have 
developed problems and they are correcting problems they will 
discard what doesnt work and keep what works the chinese are doing 
a similar trial and error hall said in an interview thursday i 
think much of it will stick theres an experimentation with a 
market economy and doing away with some of the centralization 
that had taken place 
the communist party usa advocates cooperatives and mom and 
