<TEXT>
a longdelayed inquest into the 
police killing of three unarmed ira men is putting british justice 
in northern ireland to another of its periodic tests of credibility 
it took six years to get the inquest going but within hours of 
starting nov 14 it was mired in controversy with families 
demanding police be crossexamined 
the hearing in the courtroom in craigavon county armagh is the 
latest chapter in a debate that has raged since 1982 over whether 
the british in their war against the irish republican army 
sometimes step beyond the law and shoot suspects dead on sight 
there were three such incidents in 1982 another occurred in 
gibraltar in march when antiterrorist agents gunned down three 
unarmed bombing suspects a muchdisputed inquest cleared the agents 
of wrongdoing 
and this summer after an ira bomb killed eight soldiers on a 
bus three armed ira men were gunned down allegedly while on an 
assassination mission 
the british government denies it ever acted outside the law but 
many critics question this and the issue has bedeviled government 
efforts to prove itself evenhanded in its treatment of the 
provinces catholic minority 
major initiatives like new antidiscrimination laws improved 
housing and education and investment in the strifetorn economy 
tend to be obscured by the lingering catholic refusal to believe in 
british justice 
gervase mckerr 31 and eugene toman and sean burns both 21 
were killed on nov 11 1982 as they drove on a road in lurgan 
county armagh 
their inquest began in september 1983 but was adjourned until now 
because of the trial of the three policemen who were acquitted of 
murder charges and the police refusal to turn over photographs and 
statements to defense attorneys 
at their trial the three policemen testified that they believed 
toman and burns intended to attack the security forces and did not 
know the three were unarmed 
families of two of the ira men walked out on the inquests first 
day because the coroner refused to order the three policemen who 
carried out the killings to appear in court he cited rules unique 
to northern ireland which allow witnesses to submit written 
statements without ever appearing for crossexamination 
the families want the policemen crossexamined under oath 
the wife of the third victim failed to win a high court ruling 
against the coroner and has turned to the appeals court the 
inquest meanwhile is adjourned pending the appeals court hearing 
at one point seamus mallon deputy leader of the moderate social 
democratic and labor party the provinces largest catholic party 
got so upset at the inquest that he jumped from his public gallery 
seat to demand that the police testify 
i make this request in the interests of creating a proper 
system of justice in the north of ireland mallon said i plead 
with you not to let it be turned into the charade that a vast number 
of people now believe it to be 
john stalker a senior police investigator from mainland britain 
says he was removed when he got too close to proving that police 
conspired to shoot the men possibly in revenge for the ira murder 
of three policemen and then covered up their actions 
the british government admits there was perjury and a coverup in 
the royal ulster constabulary the provinces police force but has 
ruled out prosecutions on national security grounds 
the constabulary being 85 percent protestant has a hard time 
convincing catholics that it is exercising its sweeping powers with 
restraint statistics show that less than 25 percent of those 
arrested under antiterrorism laws in the province are charged 
moreover to overcome jury intimidation security suspects are 
tried by onejudge nojury courts 
unlike in mainland britain inquest juries in northern ireland 
cannot return actual verdicts only basic findings of who died and 
when and where they were killed 
the coroner cant say that the constabulary men were guilty 
of shooting these people he cant say that these people should be 
tried theyve already been tried which is another farce says 
jackie donnelly spokesman for the outlawed iras legal political 
wing sinn fein 
amnesty international in a report in june maintained that 
northern ireland inquests cannot address questions central to the 
circumstances of deaths and to responsibility for deaths because 
they cannot return a verdict of unlawful killing 
</TEXT>
