to a public employees pension program the illinois municipal 
retirement fund 
jack edman director of legal affairs for the fund said it is 
entitled to recover the back payments by having money deducted from 
tax revenue due east st louis 
the loss of the tax money would be a devastating blow to the 
city the income and sales taxes provide about 25 million of its 
68 million budget for this year 
the city across the mississippi river from st louis mo 
suffers from an eroded industrial and commercial tax base a 
predominately poor minority population and accusations of municipal 
mismanagement 
city officials were warned about the debt in a letter from the 
pension fund dated nov 29 
weve given them 30 days from the date of the letter to work 
payment out edman said if they take no action well go to the 
state comptroller and request the money be deducted 
city attorney eric vickers said saturday he was unaware of the 
threat to seize the citys state tax revenues were certainly 
going to take whatever action is necessary to prevent them from 
doing that vickers said 
the city does not have the money in the bank to pay the debt 
officials said 
in fact a purchasing official warned in a memo last week that 
the city did not even have enough money to order toilet paper and 
cleaning supplies which he said were dangerously low the st louis 
postdispatch reported sunday 
the city was able to pay its 200 employees last week only because 
treasurer charlotte r moore drove to the capitol to pick up a 
139000 check for the citys share of state income tax revenue 
employees still are one paycheck behind 
the citys debt to the pension fund has been growing steadily 
since 1979 edman said 
robert l cusma executive director of the fund said city 
retirees could be affected if we dont get the money we cant 
pay the pensions owed them he said id be quite perturbed if 
i were a city employee 
